                        <note n="1" xml:id="note-t-1">
                            

<p><rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_787">Tersteeg</rs> had visited Theo in Paris (<ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let204.xml">see letter 204</ref>).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="2" xml:id="note-t-2">
                            

<p>Van Gogh is not necessarily referring to size when he calls this a ‘little drawing’; he could be alluding to the fact that it is not very elaborate (cf. <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let237.xml#n-10">letter 237, n. 10</ref>). It is possible that he is referring to <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">Woman at the window, knitting</hi> (<rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#noill_687">F 910a / JH 90</rs>), which <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_787">Tersteeg</rs> owned; it measures 33 x 26 cm. (The drawings he made for <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_422">Uncle Cor</rs>, which are comparable in format, were also referred to by Van Gogh as little.)</p>
                        </note>
                        
                            

                        
                    
